{"title_page": "Frederick Luis Aldama", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Frederick Luis Aldama\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            =\n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1969|03|06}}\n| birth_place      = Mexico City, Mexico\n| occupation       = Distinguished University Professor, Author\n| alma_mater       = PhD, Stanford University (1999), BA, University of California, Berkeley (1992),\n| discipline       = fiction, non-fiction, film studies, pop culture, comics\n| notable_works    = Long Story Cut Short (2017), Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics (2018)\n| awards           = [[List of Eisner Award winners|Eisner Award (2018)]]\n| website          = {{url|professorlatinx.com}}\n}}\n'''Frederick Luis Aldama''' is the [https://odi.osu.edu/laser/laser-odi/laser-news-archive/aldama-named-distinguished-university-professor.html University Distinguished Professor], Arts and Humanities Distinguished Professor of English and University Distinguished Scholar at The [[Ohio State University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osu.edu/universityawards/2014/scholar.html|title=University Distinguished Scholar Award 2014 - University Awards & Recognition - The Ohio State University|website=www.osu.edu|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> [[United States]]. In the departments of [[English department|English]] as well as [[Spanish language|Spanish]] & [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], he teaches courses on and [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] & [[Latin American culture|Latin American]] cultural phenomena, including literature, film, TV, music, sports, video games, and comic books.<ref>https://english.osu.edu/people/aldama.1</ref> He is also an affiliate faculty of the Center for Cognitive and Behavioral [[Brain imaging|Brain Imaging]].<ref>https://cog.osu.edu/directory</ref> He is the author, co-author, and editor of thirty six books, including the 2018 International Latino Book Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/2018/06/ilba-finalists|title=International Latino Book Awards Finalists \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> and [[Eisner Award]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robsalkowitz/2018/07/21/diversity-rules-at-comics-biggest-awards-night/#73538ced7d7c|title=Diversity Rules At Comics' Biggest Awards Night|last=Salkowitz|first=Rob|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> winning ''Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/book/latinx-superheroes-in-mainstream-comics|title=Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> He is the founder and director of the [[White House Initiative on Educational Excellence for Hispanics|Obama White House Hispanic Bright Spot]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/inits/list/hispanic-initiative/bright-spots.html?queries%5Bsearch%5D=ohio|title=Bright Spots: White House Initiative on Educational Excellence for Hispanics|date=2016-08-16|website=www2.ed.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> awarded LASER (Latinx Space for Enrichment Research).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://odi.osu.edu/laser/|title=LASER Home {{!}} LASER {{!}} Office of Diversity and Inclusion|last=Inclusion|first=\u00a9 2018 The Ohio State University Office of Diversity and|website=odi.osu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>  In 2016, Aldama received the Ohio Education Summit Award for Founding & Directing LASER.<ref>http://ochla.ohio.gov/EventsCalendar/OCHLAAnnualEvents/OhioLatinoEducationSummit/LatinoEducationSummit2016.aspx\n</ref> He is founder and co-director of Humanities & Cognitive Sciences High School Summer Institute at [[The Ohio State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://u.osu.edu/fowler.40/|title=Humanities & Cognitive Sciences High School Summer Institute|website=u.osu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>  He has been honored with the 2016 American Association of Hispanics in Higher Education's Outstanding Latino/a Faculty Award.  Aldama is creator and curator of [http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/ Planetary Republic of Comics]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/|title=Planetary Republic of Comics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u2014a platform for accessible scholarly knowledge about comic books and graphic nonfiction from around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/|title=Planetary Republic of Comics|work=Professor LatinX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAldama was born in [[Mexico City]] to a [[Guatemala]]n/[[Irish people|Irish]] American mother from [[Los Angeles]] and a [[Mexico|Mexican]] father from Mexico City. When he was a child, his mother moved the family to [[California]]. He received his [[undergraduate degree]] ''summa cum laude'' in English from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1992 and obtained his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] from [[Stanford University]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.osu.edu/people/aldama.1|title=Frederick Luis Aldama|date=2011-06-08|website=Department of English|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Academic work and interests==\nAldama uses [[narrative theory]], [[cognitive science]], and insights from Latinx & Latin American critical cultural theory in his teaching and scholarship on Latino & Latin American cultural phenomena: literature, art, music, film, TV, sports, video games, and comic books. He edits several book series, including the ''Contemporary Latinx & Latin American Profiles''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upress.pitt.edu/renderHtmlPage.aspx?srcHtml=htmlSourceFiles/Series/llap.htm|title=browse|website=www.upress.pitt.edu|access-date=2018-07-25}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/890170636 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/888953194 cite #14 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> series with the [[University of Pittsburgh Press]], the Global Media & Race series and Critical Graphics series with Rutgers University Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/search-list?series=global-media-and-race|title=Global Media & Race series and Critical Graphics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He co-edits ''Latinx Pop Culture''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/series/lpc|title=Latinx Pop Culture \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/890170636 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/888953194 cite #15 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> for the University of Arizona Press, the ''Cognitive Approaches to Literature and Culture'' and ''Studies for the Ohio State University Press'' as well as the ''World Comics and Graphic Nonfiction'' for the [[University of Texas Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://utpress.utexas.edu/books/series/world-comics-and-graphic-nonfiction-series|title=World Comics and Graphic Nonfiction Series|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also edits the [https://ohiostatepress.org/books/series/latinographix.html Latinographix] trade graphic and comic books series that showcase graphic novels, memoir, nonfiction, and more by Latinx writers and artists, including ''Tales from la Vida: A Latinx Comics Anthology''. He is author of the forthcoming sci-fi graphic novel, ''2041'' and two children's book, ''With Pap\u00e1''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/Series%20Pages/latinographix.html|title=Latinographix: The Ohio State Latinx Comics Series|website=ohiostatepress.org|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>https://ohiostatepress.org/books/Series%20Pages/latinographix.html</ref> and ''The Adventures of Charlie the Chupacabra.'' Aldama's fiction and graphic fiction has been published in ''Santa Clara Review'' and ''Pacific Review'', as well as in book form with ''Long Stories Cut Short: Fictions from the Borderlands'' (2017). And, he is creator of the first [[Documentary film|documentary]] on the history of Latinx superheroes in mainstream comics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://professorlatinx.com/latinx-superheroes-in-mainstream-comics-the-documentary/|title=Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics: The Documentary|work=Professor LatinX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> He is co-founder and director of S\u00d5L-CON: Brown & Black Comics Expo,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://odi.osu.edu/laser/programming/sol-con-the-brown-and-black-comix-expo/|title=S\u00d5L-CON: The Brown and Black Comix Expo {{!}} LASER {{!}} Office of Diversity and Inclusion|last=Inclusion|first=2018 The Ohio State University Office of Diversity and|website=odi.osu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> the nation's only collegiate comic book expo that focuses on the work of Black and Latinx artists, writers, editors, inkers, pencillers, filmmakers and authors. He sits on the executive council of the ''International Society for the Study of Narrative'' and on the editorial boards for journals such as ''Narrative'', \"''INKS'': ''The Journal of Comics Societ''y\", and ''The Journal of Narrative Theory''. He is a member of the standing board for the Oxford Bibliographies in Latino Studies.\n\nAldama's articles, reviews, and interviews have appeared in such journals as ''[[Aztl\u00e1n (journal)|Aztl\u00e1n]]'', ''College Literature'', ''Poets & Writers'', ''[[World Literature Today]]'', ''Cross Cultural Poetics'', ''Lit: Literature Interpretation Theory'', ''Lucero'', ''[[Comparative Literature]]'', ''[[Callaloo (journal)|The Callaloo Journal]]'', ''Nepantla, Journal of Interdisciplinary Literary Analysis'', ''[[American Literature (journal)|American Literature]]'', ''[[Latin American Research Review]]'', ''[[Modern Fiction Studies]]'', ''[[Modern Drama]]'', ''[[SubStance]]'', ''Style'', ''ImageTexT'', ''Latino Studies Projections: The Journal of Movies and Mind'', ''Alter/nativas: revista de estudios culturales latinoamericanos,  Symplok\u0113, Narrative, Interdisciplinary Literary Studies,  Style, ELN'',  and ''[[Journal of the West]]''. Interviews with Aldama have appeared in [[ABC News]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/ohio-state-professor-hopes-to-inspire-diversity-in-comic-movies|title=Ohio State professor hopes to inspire diversity in comic movies|last=WSYX/WTTE|work=WSYX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[PBS]], [[Fox News Latino]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/lifestyle/2013/02/21/dc-comics-unveils-revamped-latino-super-hero.html|title=DC Comics Unveils Revamped Latino Superhero|last=Garcia|first=Victor|date=2013-02-22|work=Fox News|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[CNN]], VOXXI, [[MSNBC]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/road-map/watch/the-barriers-for-mexican-filmmakers-in-the-us-601107523843|title=The barriers for Mexican filmmakers in the US|work=MSNBC.com|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Telemundo]]; [[The Washington Post|Washington Post,]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2015/10/02/can-comics-unite-minority-students-today-sol-con-founder-tests-his-belief/|title=Can comics unite minority students? Today, Sol-Con founder tests his belief.|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Channel 10 news.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/local-professors-look-how-captain-marvel-movie-changing-comic-book-stereotypes-2019-mar|title=Local Professors Look How Captain Marvel Movie Changing Comic Book Stereotypes|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAldama's featured interviews with authors \"Interventions\" appears quarterly in the ''American Book Review,'' where he is also an Associate Editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanbookreview.org/|title=Academic Book Review|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Aldama published his first book of fiction, ''Long Stories Cut Short: Fictions from the Borderlands''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uapress.arizona.edu/Books/bid2681.htm|title=Long Stories Cut Short \u2013 UAPress|website=www.uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Aldama's current fiction has been praised by ''Pasatiempo'' as \"''pitched perfect for depicting marginalized lives.''<ref>http://www.santafenewmexican.com/pasatiempo/books/book_reviews/long-stories-cut-short-fictions-from-the-borderlands-by-frederick/article_b375a303-8f9e-509d-a1d6-30a1274de78b.html</ref>\n\n== Selected awards ==\n\n* [https://english.osu.edu/news/aldama-receives-hartmann-mentoring-and-leadership-award 2018-2019 Susan M. Hartmann Mentoring and Leadership Award] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.osu.edu/news/aldama-receives-hartmann-mentoring-and-leadership-award|title=Aldama Receives Hartmann Mentoring and Leadership Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://www.facebook.com/OSUSPPO/posts/10156985505003006 2018-2019 Rodica C. Botoman Award for Distinguished Undergraduate Teaching and Mentoring.]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/OSUSPPO/posts/10156985505003006|title=2018-2019 Rodico Botoman Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 20 [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/2018-eisner-awards-complete-winners-list-1128983 18 Eisner Winner-'''Best Academic/Scholarly Work''' ''Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics'']<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/2018-eisner-awards-complete-winners-list-1128983|title=Eisner Awards Complete List|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 2018 International Latino Book Award for Best Nonfiction<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/2018/09/our-2018-international-latino-book-awards-winners|title=2018 International Latino Book Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://artsandsciences.osu.edu/april-5-2017 2017 Alumni Award for Distinguished Teaching and inducted into the Academy of Teaching]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsandsciences.osu.edu/april-5-2017|title=OSU Arts & Sciences: News & Updates|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://ochla.ohio.gov/Events-Calendar/OCHLA-Annual-Events/Ohio-Latino-Education-Summit/Latino-Education-Summit-2016 2016 American Association of Hispanics in Higher Education\u2019s Outstanding Latino/a Faculty Award]\n* [https://ochla.ohio.gov/Events-Calendar/OCHLA-Annual-Events/Ohio-Latino-Education-Summit/Latino-Education-Summit-2016 2016 Ohio Education Summit Award for Founding & Directing LASER]\n* 2015 White House \u201cHispanic Education Bright Spot\u201d Award for Founding & Directing LASER\u00a0 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsandsciences.osu.edu/news-events/asc-spotlights/frederick-luis-aldama|title=ASC Spotlight|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u00a0\n* [https://www.osu.edu/universityawards/2014/scholar.html 2014 Arts and Humanities Distinguished Professor]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osu.edu/universityawards/2014/scholar.html|title=University Awards and Recognitions|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 2014 University Emerging Community Engagement Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sppo.osu.edu/news/emerging-community-engagement-award|title=Emerging Community Engagement Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n* 2013 City of Columbus Diversity & Outreach Award \n* 2008 [https://www.osu.edu/facultystaff-web/university_awards/2008/diversity.php University Distinguished Diversity Enhancement Award]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osu.edu/facultystaff-web/university_awards/2008/diversity.php|title=2008 Distinguished Diversity Enhancement Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://www.mla.org/Resources/Career/MLA-Grants-and-Awards/Winners-of-MLA-Prizes/Biennial-Prize-and-Award-Winners/MLA-Prize-in-United-States-Latina-and-Latino-and-Chicana-and-Chicano-Literary-and-Cultural-Studies-Winners 2004 MLA Award: Outstanding Scholarly Book Chicano/Latino Studies]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mla.org/Resources/Career/MLA-Grants-and-Awards/Winners-of-MLA-Prizes/Biennial-Prize-and-Award-Winners/MLA-Prize-in-United-States-Latina-and-Latino-and-Chicana-and-Chicano-Literary-and-Cultural-Studies-Winners|title=MLA Prize in United States Latina and Latino and Chicana and Chicano Literary and Cultural Studies Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n* [http://nrc58.nas.edu/FordFellowDirect/Main/SearchDetailDisplay.aspx?Check=123&ALL=&ANY=&TNAD=106298 1999 Ford Foundation Fellowship]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nrc58.nas.edu/FordFellowDirect/Main/SearchDetailDisplay.aspx?Check=123&ALL=&ANY=&TNAD=106298|title=Ford Foundation Fellowship Program|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n* 1993-1996 Mellon Foundation Fellowship. Declined.\n\n==Books published==\n* ''Postethnic Narrative Criticism''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Postethnic Narrative Criticism Magicorealism in Oscar 'zeta' Acosta, Anna Castillo, Julie Dash, Hanif Kureishi, and Salman Rushdie.|date=2009|publisher=Univ of Texas Pr|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis.|isbn=9780292722101|oclc=320192033}}</ref>(University of Texas Press, 2003)\n* ''Arturo Islas: The Uncollected Works''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Arturo Islas : the uncollected works|last=1938-1991.|first=Islas, Arturo|date=2003|publisher=Arte P\u00fablico Press|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9781611920642|location=Houston|oclc=606994143}}</ref> (Arte P\u00fablico Press, 2003)\n* ''Dancing With Ghosts: A Critical Biography of Arturo Islas.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dancing with ghosts : a critical biography of Arturo Islas|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2005|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520938540|location=Berkeley|oclc=57207131}}</ref> Winner of the MLA Prize in United States Latina and Latino and Chicana and Chicano Literary and Cultural Studies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mla.org/Resources/Career/MLA-Grants-and-Awards/Winners-of-MLA-Prizes/Biennial-Prize-and-Award-Winners/MLA-Prize-in-United-States-Latina-and-Latino-and-Chicana-and-Chicano-Literary-and-Cultural-Studies-Winners|title=MLA Prize in United States Latina and Latino and Chicana and...|website=Modern Language Association|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>''(University of California Press, 2004)''\n* ''Brown on Brown: Chicano/a Representations of Gender, Sexuality and Ethnicity''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brown on brown : Chicano/a representations of gender, sexuality, and ethnicity|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2005|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=0292796587|edition= 1st|location=Austin|oclc=62746185}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2005)\n* ''Critical Mappings of Arturo Islas's Narrative Fictions''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Critical mappings of Arturo Islas's fictions|date=2008|publisher=Bilingual Press/Editorial Biling\u00fce|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=978-1931010313|location=Tempe, Ariz.|oclc=55878022}}</ref> (Bilingual Press], 2005)\n* ''Spilling the Beans in Chicanolandia: Conversations with Artists and Writers''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Spilling the beans in Chicanolandia : conversations with writers and artists|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2006|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=0292795939|edition= 1st|location=Austin|oclc=69199653}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2006)\n* ''Why the Humanities Matter: A Common Sense Approach''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Why the humanities matter : a commonsense approach|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2008|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292717985|edition= 1st |location=Austin|oclc=179786739}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2008)\n* ''Your Brain On Latino Comics: From Gus Arriola to Los Bros Hernandez\"''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Your brain on Latino comics : from Gus Arriola to Los Bros Hernandez|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292795211|edition= 1st |location=Austin|oclc=429911628}}</ref> ''(University of Texas Press, 2008)''\n* ''A User's Guide to Postcolonial and Latino Borderland Fiction'' <ref>{{Cite book|title=A user's guide to postcolonial and Latino borderland fiction|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292719682|edition= 1st |location=Austin|oclc=288932889}}</ref>(University of Texas Press, 2009)\n* ''Multicultural Comics: From Zap to Blue Beetle''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Multicultural comics : from Zap to Blue Beetle|last=|first=|date=2011|publisher=University Of Texas Press|isbn=978-0292737433|location=Austin|pages=|oclc=773258062}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2010)\n* ''Toward a Cognitive Theory of Narrative Acts''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Toward a cognitive theory of narrative acts|date=2010|publisher=University of Texas Press|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9780292721579|edition= 1st |location=Austin|oclc=471787942}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2010)\n* ''Analyzing World Fiction: New Horizons in Narrative Theory''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Analyzing world fiction : new horizons in narrative theory|date=2012|publisher=University of Texas Press|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9780292747647|edition= 1st paperback|location=Austin|oclc=829884734}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2011)\n* ''The Routledge Concise History of Latino/a Literature'' <ref>{{Cite book|title=The Routledge concise history of Latino/a literature|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415667876|location=New York|oclc=779258509}}</ref>(Routledge, 2012)\n* ''Formal Matters in Contemporary Latino Poetry''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Formal matters in contemporary Latino poetry|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|isbn=9780230391635|location=New York|oclc=829739896}}</ref> (Palgrave, 2013)\n* ''Mex-Cin\u00e9: Mexican Filmmaking, Production, and Consumption in the Twenty-first Century''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mex-Cine : Mexican filmmaking, production, and consumption in the twenty-first century|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|date=2013|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472029129|location=Ann Arbor|oclc=844924402}}</ref> (University of Michigan Press, 2013)\n* ''Latinos and Narrative Media: Participation and Portrayal''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latinos and narrative media : participation and portrayal|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9781137366450|edition= First|location=New York|oclc=845085678|date = 2013-11-07}}</ref> (Palgrave, 2013)\n* ''\u00a1Muy Pop! Conversations on Latino Popular Culture.'' Co-authored with Ilan Stavans<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u00a1Muy Pop! : conversations on Latino popular culture|last=Ilan.|first=Stavans|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9780472029440|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|oclc=874149423}}</ref> (University of Michigan, 2013)\n* ''Latinos in the End Zone: Conversations on the Brown Color Line in the NFL.'' Co-authored with Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latinos in the end zone : conversations on the brown color line in the NFL|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|others=Gonz\u00e1lez, Christopher|isbn=978-1137403087|edition= First|location=New York, NY|oclc=860395198|date = 2013-11-15}}</ref> (Palgrave, 2013)\n* ''Conversations on Cognitive Cultural Studies: Literature, Language, Aesthetics.'' Co-authored with Patrick Colm Hogan<ref>{{Cite book|title=Conversations on cognitive cultural studies : literature, language, and aesthetics|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|others=Hogan, Patrick Colm|isbn=9780814212431|location=Columbus|oclc=861955952|year = 2014}}</ref> (Ohio State U Press, 2014)\n* ''The Cinema of Robert Rodriguez''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The cinema of Robert Rodriguez|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|isbn=9780292761216|edition= First|location=Austin|oclc=878667406|date = 2014-10-15}}</ref>''.'' (University of Texas Press, 2014)\n* ''Critical Approaches to the Films of Robert Rodriguez.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Critical approaches to the films of Robert Rodriguez|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9780292763555|edition= First |location=Austin|oclc=881720711|date = 2015-03-15}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2015)\n* ''Latino Literature in the Classroom: 21st Century Approaches to Teaching''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latino/a literature in the classroom : twenty-first century approaches to teaching|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9780415724203|location=London|oclc=852219289|year = 2015}}</ref> (Routledge, 2015)\n* ''The Aesthetics of Discomfort''. Co-authored with Herbert Lindenberger.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Aesthetics of discomfort : conversations on disquieting art|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|others=Lindenberger, Herbert, 1929-|isbn=9780472073009|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|oclc=930257206}}</ref>(University of Michigan Press, 2016).\n*''Laughing Matters: Conversations on Humor.'' Co-authored with Ilan Stavans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Laughing matters : conversations on humor|last=Ilan|first=Stavans|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=978-1938537912|location=San Diego, Calif.|oclc=940997852|year = 2016}}</ref>(San Diego State University Press,2016)\n*''Graphic Borders: Latino Comic Books Past, Present, and Future''. Co-edited with Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Graphic borders : Latino comic books past, present, and future|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-, Gonz\u00e1lez, Christopher|isbn=9781477309148|edition= First |location=Austin|oclc=920966195|date = 2016-04-12}}</ref> (University of Texas Press, 2016)\n*''The Routledge Companion to Latina/o Popular Culture''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Routledge companion to Latina/o popular culture|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9781317268192|location=New York|oclc=931226946|date = 2016-05-26}}</ref>''.'' (Routledge, 2016)\n*''Latinx Comic Book Storytelling: An Odyssey by Interview.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latinx comic book storytelling : an odyssey by interview|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|others=Padilla, Ricardo,, Fern\u00e1ndez l'Hoeste, H\u00e9ctor D., 1962-, Gonz\u00e1lez, Christopher|isbn=978-1938537929|edition= First |location=San Diego, CA|oclc=973339575|year = 2016}}</ref> San Diego State University Press, 2016\n*''Long Stories Cut Short: Fictions from the Borderlands. English & Spanish. Fiction''.Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 2017<ref>{{Cite book|title=Long stories cut short : fictions from the borderlands|last=Luis|first=Aldama, Frederick|isbn=9780816536115|location=Tucson|oclc=965129760|date = 2017-02-07}}</ref>\n*''Latinx Superhero in the Mainstream''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/book/latinx-superheroes-in-mainstream-comics|title=Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref>  Eisner Award Winner: Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 2017\n*''Tales from la Vida: A Latinx Comics Anthology (Latinographix)''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/titles/9780814254936.html|title=Tales from la Vida: A Latinx Comics Anthology|website=ohiostatepress.org|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> Editor: Columbus: Ohio State University Press, 2018\n*''Latinx Studies: The Key Concepts''. Co-authored with Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez. (Routledge, 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|title=LATINA/ O STUDIES : key concepts.|last=FREDERICK.|first=ALDAMA|date=2018|publisher=ROUTLEDGE|isbn=978-1138088443|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1012346313}}</ref>\n*''Comics Studies Here and Now'' Editor. (Routledge, 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Comics studies here and now|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9781351015271|location=New York, NY|oclc=1022076511}}</ref>\n*''The Routledge Companion to Gender, Sex and Pop Culture in Latin America''. Editor (Routledge, 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Routledge companion to gender, sex and Latin American culture|others=Aldama, Frederick Luis, 1969-|isbn=9781315179728|location=Abingdon, Oxon|oclc=1038269645}}</ref>\n*''Latino/a Children and Young Adult Writers on the Art of Storytelling.'' (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latino/a children's and young adult writers on the art of storytelling|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|isbn=082296497X|location=Pittsburgh, Pa.|oclc=989035334}}</ref>\n*''The Oxford Handbook of Comic Book Studies'' (Oxford University Press, 2019)''.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Handbook of Comic Book Studies|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=9780190917944|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Talking #browntv: Latinas and Latinos on Screen'' (OSU Press, 2019)''.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Talking #browntv: Latinas and Latinos on the Screen|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=0814255590|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Reel Latinxs: Representation in US Film & TV.'' Co-authored with Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez (University of Arizona Press, 2019).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reel Latinxs: Representation in US Film & TV.|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|last2=Gonzalez|first2=Christopher|publisher=University of Arizona Press|year=|isbn=0816539588|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n*''Latinx Cin\u00e9 in the Twenty-First Century (University of Arizona Press, 2019). Editor.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latinx Cin\u00e9 in the Twenty-First Century.|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=University of Arizona, Press|year=2019|isbn=978-0816537907|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Jeff Smith: Conversations. University Press of Mississippi (November 15, 2019). Editor''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Jeff Smith: Conversations|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|year=2019|isbn=978-1496824806|location=Jeff Smith: Conversations|pages=}}</ref>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aldama, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Frederick Luis Aldama\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            =\n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1969|03|06}}\n| birth_place      = Mexico City, Mexico\n| occupation       = Distinguished University Professor, Author\n| alma_mater       = PhD, Stanford University (1999), BA, University of California, Berkeley (1992),\n| discipline       = fiction, non-fiction, film studies, pop culture, comics\n| notable_works    = Long Story Cut Short (2017), Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics (2018)\n| awards           = [[List of Eisner Award winners|Eisner Award (2018)]]\n| website          = {{url|professorlatinx.com}}\n}}\n'''Frederick Luis Aldama''' is the [https://odi.osu.edu/laser/laser-odi/laser-news-archive/aldama-named-distinguished-university-professor.html University Distinguished Professor], Arts and Humanities Distinguished Professor of English and University Distinguished Scholar at The [[Ohio State University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osu.edu/universityawards/2014/scholar.html|title=University Distinguished Scholar Award 2014 - University Awards & Recognition - The Ohio State University|website=www.osu.edu|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> [[United States]]. In the departments of [[English department|English]] as well as [[Spanish language|Spanish]] & [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], he teaches courses on and [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] & [[Latin American culture|Latin American]] cultural phenomena, including literature, film, TV, music, sports, video games, and comic books.<ref>https://english.osu.edu/people/aldama.1</ref> He is also an affiliate faculty of the Center for Cognitive and Behavioral [[Brain imaging|Brain Imaging]].<ref>https://cog.osu.edu/directory</ref> He is the author, co-author, and editor of thirty six books, including the 2018 International Latino Book Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/2018/06/ilba-finalists|title=International Latino Book Awards Finalists \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> and [[Eisner Award]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robsalkowitz/2018/07/21/diversity-rules-at-comics-biggest-awards-night/#73538ced7d7c|title=Diversity Rules At Comics' Biggest Awards Night|last=Salkowitz|first=Rob|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> winning ''Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/book/latinx-superheroes-in-mainstream-comics|title=Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> He is the founder and director of the [[White House Initiative on Educational Excellence for Hispanics|Obama White House Hispanic Bright Spot]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/inits/list/hispanic-initiative/bright-spots.html?queries%5Bsearch%5D=ohio|title=Bright Spots: White House Initiative on Educational Excellence for Hispanics|date=2016-08-16|website=www2.ed.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> awarded LASER (Latinx Space for Enrichment Research).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://odi.osu.edu/laser/|title=LASER Home {{!}} LASER {{!}} Office of Diversity and Inclusion|last=Inclusion|first=\u00a9 2018 The Ohio State University Office of Diversity and|website=odi.osu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>  In 2016, Aldama received the Ohio Education Summit Award for Founding & Directing LASER.<ref>http://ochla.ohio.gov/EventsCalendar/OCHLAAnnualEvents/OhioLatinoEducationSummit/LatinoEducationSummit2016.aspx\n</ref> He is founder and co-director of Humanities & Cognitive Sciences High School Summer Institute at [[The Ohio State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://u.osu.edu/fowler.40/|title=Humanities & Cognitive Sciences High School Summer Institute|website=u.osu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>  He has been honored with the 2016 American Association of Hispanics in Higher Education's Outstanding Latino/a Faculty Award.  Aldama is creator and curator of [http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/ Planetary Republic of Comics]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/|title=Planetary Republic of Comics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\u2014a platform for accessible scholarly knowledge about comic books and graphic nonfiction from around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://professorlatinx.com/planetary-republic-of-comics/|title=Planetary Republic of Comics|work=Professor LatinX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAldama was born in [[Mexico City]] to a [[Guatemala]]n/[[Irish people|Irish]] American mother from [[Los Angeles]] and a [[Mexico|Mexican]] father from Mexico City. When he was a child, his mother moved the family to [[California]]. He received his [[undergraduate degree]] ''summa cum laude'' in English from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1992 and obtained his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] from [[Stanford University]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.osu.edu/people/aldama.1|title=Frederick Luis Aldama|date=2011-06-08|website=Department of English|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Academic work and interests==\nAldama uses [[narrative theory]], [[cognitive science]], and insights from Latinx & Latin American critical cultural theory in his teaching and scholarship on Latino & Latin American cultural phenomena: literature, art, music, film, TV, sports, video games, and comic books. He edits several book series, including the ''Contemporary Latinx & Latin American Profiles''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upress.pitt.edu/renderHtmlPage.aspx?srcHtml=htmlSourceFiles/Series/llap.htm|title=browse|website=www.upress.pitt.edu|access-date=2018-07-25}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/890170636 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/888953194 cite #14 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> series with the [[University of Pittsburgh Press]], the Global Media & Race series and Critical Graphics series with Rutgers University Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rutgersuniversitypress.org/search-list?series=global-media-and-race|title=Global Media & Race series and Critical Graphics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He co-edits ''Latinx Pop Culture''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/series/lpc|title=Latinx Pop Culture \u2013 UAPress|website=uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/890170636 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/888953194 cite #15 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> for the University of Arizona Press, the ''Cognitive Approaches to Literature and Culture'' and ''Studies for the Ohio State University Press'' as well as the ''World Comics and Graphic Nonfiction'' for the [[University of Texas Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://utpress.utexas.edu/books/series/world-comics-and-graphic-nonfiction-series|title=World Comics and Graphic Nonfiction Series|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also edits the [https://ohiostatepress.org/books/series/latinographix.html Latinographix] trade graphic and comic books series that showcase graphic novels, memoir, nonfiction, and more by Latinx writers and artists, including ''Tales from la Vida: A Latinx Comics Anthology''. He is author of the forthcoming sci-fi graphic novel, ''2041'' and two children's book, ''With Pap\u00e1''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/Series%20Pages/latinographix.html|title=Latinographix: The Ohio State Latinx Comics Series|website=ohiostatepress.org|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>https://ohiostatepress.org/books/Series%20Pages/latinographix.html</ref> and ''The Adventures of Charlie the Chupacabra.'' Aldama's fiction and graphic fiction has been published in ''Santa Clara Review'' and ''Pacific Review'', as well as in book form with ''Long Stories Cut Short: Fictions from the Borderlands'' (2017). And, he is creator of the first [[Documentary film|documentary]] on the history of Latinx superheroes in mainstream comics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://professorlatinx.com/latinx-superheroes-in-mainstream-comics-the-documentary/|title=Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics: The Documentary|work=Professor LatinX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> He is co-founder and director of S\u00d5L-CON: Brown & Black Comics Expo,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://odi.osu.edu/laser/programming/sol-con-the-brown-and-black-comix-expo/|title=S\u00d5L-CON: The Brown and Black Comix Expo {{!}} LASER {{!}} Office of Diversity and Inclusion|last=Inclusion|first=2018 The Ohio State University Office of Diversity and|website=odi.osu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> the nation's only collegiate comic book expo that focuses on the work of Black and Latinx artists, writers, editors, inkers, pencillers, filmmakers and authors. He sits on the executive council of the ''International Society for the Study of Narrative'' and on the editorial boards for journals such as ''Narrative'', \"''INKS'': ''The Journal of Comics Societ''y\", and ''The Journal of Narrative Theory''. He is a member of the standing board for the Oxford Bibliographies in Latino Studies.\n\nAldama's articles, reviews, and interviews have appeared in such journals as ''[[Aztl\u00e1n (journal)|Aztl\u00e1n]]'', ''College Literature'', ''Poets & Writers'', ''[[World Literature Today]]'', ''Cross Cultural Poetics'', ''Lit: Literature Interpretation Theory'', ''Lucero'', ''[[Comparative Literature]]'', ''[[Callaloo (journal)|The Callaloo Journal]]'', ''Nepantla, Journal of Interdisciplinary Literary Analysis'', ''[[American Literature (journal)|American Literature]]'', ''[[Latin American Research Review]]'', ''[[Modern Fiction Studies]]'', ''[[Modern Drama]]'', ''[[SubStance]]'', ''Style'', ''ImageTexT'', ''Latino Studies Projections: The Journal of Movies and Mind'', ''Alter/nativas: revista de estudios culturales latinoamericanos,  Symplok\u0113, Narrative, Interdisciplinary Literary Studies,  Style, ELN'',  and ''[[Journal of the West]]''. Interviews with Aldama have appeared in [[ABC News]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/ohio-state-professor-hopes-to-inspire-diversity-in-comic-movies|title=Ohio State professor hopes to inspire diversity in comic movies|last=WSYX/WTTE|work=WSYX|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[PBS]], [[Fox News Latino]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/lifestyle/2013/02/21/dc-comics-unveils-revamped-latino-super-hero.html|title=DC Comics Unveils Revamped Latino Superhero|last=Garcia|first=Victor|date=2013-02-22|work=Fox News|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[CNN]], VOXXI, [[MSNBC]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/road-map/watch/the-barriers-for-mexican-filmmakers-in-the-us-601107523843|title=The barriers for Mexican filmmakers in the US|work=MSNBC.com|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Telemundo]]; [[The Washington Post|Washington Post,]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2015/10/02/can-comics-unite-minority-students-today-sol-con-founder-tests-his-belief/|title=Can comics unite minority students? Today, Sol-Con founder tests his belief.|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Channel 10 news.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/local-professors-look-how-captain-marvel-movie-changing-comic-book-stereotypes-2019-mar|title=Local Professors Look How Captain Marvel Movie Changing Comic Book Stereotypes|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAldama's featured interviews with authors \"Interventions\" appears quarterly in the ''American Book Review,'' where he is also an Associate Editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanbookreview.org/|title=Academic Book Review|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Aldama published his first book of fiction, ''Long Stories Cut Short: Fictions from the Borderlands''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uapress.arizona.edu/Books/bid2681.htm|title=Long Stories Cut Short \u2013 UAPress|website=www.uapress.arizona.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Aldama's current fiction has been praised by ''Pasatiempo'' as \"''pitched perfect for depicting marginalized lives.''<ref>http://www.santafenewmexican.com/pasatiempo/books/book_reviews/long-stories-cut-short-fictions-from-the-borderlands-by-frederick/article_b375a303-8f9e-509d-a1d6-30a1274de78b.html</ref>\n\n== Selected Awards ==\n\n* [https://english.osu.edu/news/aldama-receives-hartmann-mentoring-and-leadership-award 2018-2019 Susan M. Hartmann Mentoring and Leadership Award] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.osu.edu/news/aldama-receives-hartmann-mentoring-and-leadership-award|title=Aldama Receives Hartmann Mentoring and Leadership Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://www.facebook.com/OSUSPPO/posts/10156985505003006 2018-2019 Rodica C. Botoman Award for Distinguished Undergraduate Teaching and Mentoring.]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/OSUSPPO/posts/10156985505003006|title=2018-2019 Rodico Botoman Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 20 [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/2018-eisner-awards-complete-winners-list-1128983 18 Eisner Winner-'''Best Academic/Scholarly Work''' ''Latinx Superheroes in Mainstream Comics'']<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/2018-eisner-awards-complete-winners-list-1128983|title=Eisner Awards Complete List|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 2018 International Latino Book Award for Best Nonfiction<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uapress.arizona.edu/2018/09/our-2018-international-latino-book-awards-winners|title=2018 International Latino Book Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://artsandsciences.osu.edu/april-5-2017 2017 Alumni Award for Distinguished Teaching and inducted into the Academy of Teaching]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsandsciences.osu.edu/april-5-2017|title=OSU Arts & Sciences: News & Updates|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [https://ochla.ohio.gov/Events-Calendar/OCHLA-Annual-Events/Ohio-Latino-Educat