 Children and Young Adult Writers on the Art of Storytelling.'' (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latino/a children's and young adult writers on the art of storytelling|last=1969-|first=Aldama, Frederick Luis|isbn=082296497X|location=Pittsburgh, Pa.|oclc=989035334}}</ref>\n*''The Oxford Handbook of Comic Book Studies'' (Oxford University Press, 2019)''.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Handbook of Comic Book Studies|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=9780190917944|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Talking #browntv: Latinas and Latinos on Screen'' (OSU Press, 2019)''.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Talking #browntv: Latinas and Latinos on the Screen|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=0814255590|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Reel Latinxs: Representation in US Film & TV.'' Co-authored with Christopher Gonz\u00e1lez (University of Arizona Press, 2019).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reel Latinxs: Representation in US Film & TV.|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|last2=Gonzalez|first2=Christopher|publisher=University of Arizona Press|year=|isbn=0816539588|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n*''Latinx Cin\u00e9 in the Twenty-First Century (University of Arizona Press, 2019). Editor.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latinx Cin\u00e9 in the Twenty-First Century.|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=University of Arizona, Press|year=2019|isbn=978-0816537907|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Jeff Smith: Conversations. University Press of Mississippi (November 15, 2019). Editor''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Jeff Smith: Conversations|last=Aldama|first=Frederick|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|year=2019|isbn=978-1496824806|location=Jeff Smith: Conversations|pages=}}</ref>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aldama, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_Luis_Aldama"}
{"title_page": "John R. Seale", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = John R. Seale\n| honorific_suffix = MRCP\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1927}}\n| birth_place = Exeter, England\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education =  St John's College, Cambridge\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = Theories about the origin of HIV\n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = Physician\n| field = \n| work_institutions = \n| specialism = Venereology\n| research_field = \n| notable_works = \n| prizes = \n| child = \n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''John Richard Seale''' (born 1927) is a British [[venereologist]] and advocate in the 1980s of the now-discredited theory that [[HIV]] which causes [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] might have been created in a [[bioterrorism|germ-warfare]] laboratory by [[Genetic engineering|gene-editing]]. His views and writings were subsequently used to back-up the claims of those that proposed a man-made origin for the virus, and in [[Propaganda in the Soviet Union|Soviet propaganda]] against the United States. A collection of papers relating to Seale's views on HIV are held by the [[Wellcome Collection]].\n\n==Early life and family==\nJohn Seale was born in Exeter in 1927. He received his BA from [[St John's College, Cambridge]], in 1948<ref name=coll/> and his [[MB BChir]] in 1951.<ref>''The Medical Directory 2015''. CRC Press. p. 3723. {{ISBN|978-1498705929}}</ref> He became a member of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] (MRCP) in 1953.<ref name=well/><ref name=\":Medical1986\">{{Cite book |title=The Medical Directory|last=|first= |date=1986 |publisher=Churchill Livingstone |isbn=978-0582903661 |edition=142nd |location=London |page=2670 |oclc=15467109}}</ref> Four years later he qualified with a [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]].<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\nHe married Elisabeth C. Grillet in Cambridge in 1949.<ref name=coll>\"College Notes\", ''The Eagle'', St John's College, Cambridge, 1950, p. 69.</ref><ref>\"Marriages\", ''The Times'', 7 November 1949, p. 1.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in his career, Seale took an interest in [[health economics]]. He was Goodwin Travelling Fellow for [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]] at Harvard Graduate School of Business Administration<ref name=fixed>\"Fixed Costs in the Health Service\" by J. R. Seale in ''The Lancet'', Vol. 276, No. 7152 (24 September 1960), pp. 696\u2013698.</ref> and wrote on the relative spending on medicine in different countries, publishing on the matter in ''The Lancet'' in 1960 when he was senior medical registrar at St Mary's Hospital, London, and at the West Middlesex Hospital, Isleworth.<ref name=fixed/>\n\nIn 1966, he was appointed consultant venereologist at St Thomas' Hospital in London.<ref>\"Appointments\", ''The Lancet'', 30 July 1966, p. 288.</ref> He later worked at the [[Lister Hospital, Chelsea|Lister Hospital]].<ref name=Seale1989>{{Cite journal|last=Seale|first=John|date=1 August 1989|title=Origins of the AIDS Viruses: HIV-1 and HIV-2, Fact or Fiction?|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine|language=en|volume=82|issue=8|pages=508|doi=10.1177/014107688908200829|pmid=2778789|pmc=1292272|issn=0141-0768}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]].<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\n===Anti-NHS activism===\nIn the late 1950s, Seale became a member of the [[Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine]] (FFM), a conservative organisation that resisted the state control of medicine in Britain through the [[National Health Service]] (NHS). He was elected to the Fellowship's executive in 1962.<ref name=cow/> His writings in support of the FFM's perspective included an article on \"The Supply of Doctors\" in the ''British Medical Journal'' in 1961 and another in 1964 in that journal on the rate of medical emigration from Britain and Ireland.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Seale | first1 = John R | year = 1964 | title = Medical Emigration from Great Britain and Ireland | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/1/5391/1173 | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 1 | issue = 5391| pages = 1173\u201378 }}</ref> He identified migration of British doctors to countries such as Canada due to poor employment conditions in the NHS and migration to Britain of doctors from Asia whose training and English language skills he questioned, adding a racial component to the class-based and economic opposition of some British doctors to the imposition of the NHS system on them by the British government. Much of the migration from Britain was of [[general practitioner]]s in what was seen in the 1960s as a crisis in general practice. In 1962 he appeared on an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] television programme ''[[Questions in the House]]'' with fellow FFM member and member of Parliament Dr [[Donald McIntosh Johnson]] to discuss medical migration.<ref name=cow/>\n\nIn 1962 he undertook a speaking tour of the United States, funded by the [[American Medical Association]], as part of efforts to undermine the [[Kennedy administration]]'s proposed [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] bill. In a speech in New York on 21 May 1962, [[President Kennedy]] criticised Seale's arguments. After seeing this reported in London's ''Evening Standard'', Seale obtained a copy of the speech from the White House and sued the newspaper's publishers for misrepresenting the President's words.<ref name=cow/>\n\nSeale later became influential in health matters with the free-market supporting [[Institute for Economic Affairs]], contributing to their publications such as their occasional paper ''Towards a Welfare Society'' in 1967.<ref name=cow>{{cite journal | last1 = Seaton | first1 = Andrew | year = 2015| title = Duncan Tanner Essay Prize Winner 2014: Against the 'Sacred Cow': NHS Opposition and the Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine, 1948\u201372 | url = https://academic.oup.com/tcbh/article/26/3/424/2451908 | journal = [[Twentieth Century British History]] | volume = 26 | issue = 3| pages = 424\u2013449 | doi = 10.1093/tcbh/hwv011 }}</ref>\n\n===Views on HIV and AIDS===\nIn the 1980s, Seale advocated the now-discredited theory that [[HIV]], which causes [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], might have been created in a germ-warfare laboratory by gene-editing and released either deliberately or by accident.<ref name=LATimes/>\n\nIn mid 1985, worried by the implications of the spread of the virus, Seale argued that it had national security implication for the west by potentially diminishing the effectiveness of NATO forces to such an extent that the Soviet Union would not need to use nuclear or chemical weapons to win a war, but he continued to believe that the virus had a natural origin in monkeys.<ref name=disin>Geissler, Erhard, and Robert Hunt Sprinkle. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/43287281 \"Disinformation Squared: Was the HIV-from-Fort-Detrick Myth a Stasi Success?\"], ''[[Politics and the Life Sciences]]'', Vol. 32, No. 2, 2013, pp. 2\u201399.</ref>\n\nLater, he began to consider the possibility that the virus was man-made after reading an article by [[Valentin Zapevalov]], \"Panic in the West: or what Hides Behind the Sensationalism of AIDS\", and an interview with professor S. Drozdov, \"AIDS: Panic Continues\", published in the non-scientific ''[[Literaturnaya Gazeta]]'' in Russia in October and December 1985  respectively. Zapevalov argued that the virus might have been produced by scientists working for the U.S. military at [[Fort Detrick]] in Maryland or at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] in Atlanta, while Drozdov said that the virus was \"apparently taken out from the deepest regions of Central Africa\" thus raising the possibility that it was deliberately collected. He also stated that the virus could have been man-made.<ref name=Seale1986/><ref name=\"Largent\">{{cite book|author=Largent, Mark A.|title=Vaccine: The Debate in Modern America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gmsPMWQgmu4C&pg=RA1-PT112|year=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-1-4214-0672-5}}</ref><ref name=\"Hamb\">{{cite book|author=Hamblin, Jacob Darwin.|title=Arming Mother Nature: The Birth of Catastrophic Environmentalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNwZnNiBWUkC&pg=PA234|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-974005-5|page=234}}</ref>\n\nSeale argued that centres for biological warfare research had known about the [[Visna virus]] in sheep since 1949 which he said had a similar structure to HIV, differing by only one gene, and caused a disease with similar symptoms. He believed that HIV could have been produced by gene-editing as \"Inserting an extra gene into a virus is a routine procedure in modern genetic engineering\".<ref name=LATimes>[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-12-19/news/mn-30652_1_aids-virus AIDS Could Be Germ War Lab Product: M.D.], ''Los Angeles Times'', 19 December 1985. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref> His view that the virus could have been created in a laboratory was reported in Britain's communist ''[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]'' and on [[Radio Moscow]] who stated that it supported the possibility that the virus was made by the United States as a weapon.<ref name=disin/><ref name=med>Medvedev, Zhores A., [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1290430/ \"AIDS virus infection: A Soviet view of its origin]\". ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine''. 79 (8): 494. ISSN 0141-0768.</ref> [[Jakob Segal]], an East German biologist, later revealed to be a KGB agent, wrote to Seale in support of his views about a man-made origin for the virus.<ref name=disin/>\n\nHis views were criticised by exiled Russian dissident [[Zhores Medvedev]] in the letters page of the  ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' in August 1986 as potentially spreading Soviet disinformation.<ref name=disin/><ref name=med/> Seale's reply was printed below in which he made it clear that he did not know for sure where the virus might have been created, but maintaining the likelihood of its man-made origin. He also compared the international spread of the virus to the spread of [[myxomatosis]] in rabbits in the 1950s which had been caused by the deliberate release of two infected rabbits on an estate in France.<ref name=Seale1986>{{Cite journal|last=Seale|first=John|date=August 1986|title=Dr Seale replies|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine|volume=79|issue=8|pages=494\u2013495|issn=0141-0768|pmc=1290430}}</ref>\n\nSeale's theories were supported by his friend at St Thomas's, Henry A. Sanford, with whom he had been a medical student, and Sanford wrote in support of them in the medical and general press.<ref name=well/> Seale's views and writings, which were mostly in the form of opinion pieces, letters, and book reviews, rather than scientific papers, were used by those that advocated a man-made origin for HIV as evidence of scientific research in support of their position and may have influenced American politician [[Lyndon LaRouche]]'s views on the need to isolate those with HIV and therefore, indirectly, the proposal in California's [[1986 California Proposition 64|Proposition 64]] in 1986 to restore AIDS to the list of communicable diseases.<ref name=disin/><ref name=\"Toumey1996\">{{cite book|author=Toumey, Christopher P.|title=Conjuring Science: Scientific Symbols and Cultural Meanings in American Life|url=https://archive.org/details/conjuringscience0000toum_p4q0|url-access=registration|year=1996|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick|isbn=978-0-8135-2285-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/conjuringscience0000toum_p4q0/page/88 88]}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1987, Seale argued in a paper given before the [[Bristol Medico Chirurgical Society]], and later printed in their journal, that the threat from AIDS was so serious that only compulsory government testing and methods to prevent homosexual men infecting each other and non-homosexuals could halt it with an inevitable and justified curtailment of civil rights as occurs when a country faces war. He further argued that the use of condoms would have no effect on the spread of the disease as, in his view, dirty needles, blood, and serum were the most effective methods of transmission. He also blamed homosexuals among AIDS scientists and campaigners for perpetuating, in his view, incorrect ideas about the spread of the disease.<ref>Seale, John R. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5113556/ \"The AIDS Epidemic and Its Control\"], ''Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal'', Vol. 102, No. 3 (August 1987), pp. 66\u201368.</ref> In May 1987, Seale and [[Zhores A. Medvedev]] argued in an article in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'' that HIV in Russia was spread primarily through the re-use of poorly sterilised hypodermic needles rather than through sexual activity.<ref name=\"russ\">{{cite book|author=Mark G. Field & Judyth L. Twigg (Eds.)|title=Russia's Torn Safety Nets: Health and Social Welfare During the Transition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VsoYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA149|year=2000|publisher=St Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-349-62712-7|page=149}}</ref><ref>\"Origin and transmission of AIDS. Multi-use hypodermics and the threat to the Soviet Union: discussion paper\", John R. Seale & Zhores A. Medvedev, ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'', Vol. 80 (May 1987), pp. 201\u2013204.</ref>\n\nRecords relating to Seale's theories and his supporter Henry A. Sanford are held in the [[Wellcome Collection]] which received them from Sanford in 2013.<ref name=\"well\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.wellcomelibrary.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=(AltRefNo=%27MS.8877%27)|title=Henry Sanford: papers relating to John Seale and controversies over AIDS|last=|first=|date=|website=Wellcome Library|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===1960s===\n* \"[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140673660917670 Fixed Costs in the Health Service]\", ''The Lancet'', Vol. 276, No. 7152 (24 September 1960), pp.&nbsp;696\u2013698. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(60)91767-0\n* \"The Supply of Doctors\", ''British Medical Journal'', 2, 9 December 1961, 2, pp.&nbsp;1554\u201355.\n* ''The Supply of Doctors and the Future of the British Medical Profession''. Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine, London, 1962.\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/1/5391/1173 \"Medical Emigration from Great Britain and Ireland\"],  ''British Medical Journal'', 1964, No. 1, pp.&nbsp;1173\u201378.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 5952270 | doi=10.1136/sti.42.1.31 | volume=42 | issue=1 | title=The sexually-transmitted diseases and marriage | pmc=1047771 | year=1966 | journal=Br J Vener Dis | pages=31\u20136  | last1 = Seale | first1 = JR}}\n\n===1970s===\n*\"Vaginal discharge\" in [[Geoffrey Chamberlain]] (Ed.) (1977) ''Contemporary Obstetrics and Gynaecology''. London: Northwood.<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\n===1980s===\n* {{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/014107688507800801 | volume=78 | title=AIDS Virus Infection: Prognosis and Transmission | year=1985 | journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | pages=613\u2013615  | last1 = Seale | first1 = John}}\n* {{cite journal | pmc = 5113556 | doi = 10.1177/014107688708000402 | pmid=28906764 | volume=102 | title=The AIDS Epidemic and Its Control | year=1987 | journal=Bristol Med Chir J | pages=66\u201368  | last1 = Seale | first1 = J}}\n* {{cite journal | pmc = 1290815 | pmid=3612664 | volume=80 | title=Origin and transmission of AIDS. Multi-use hypodermics and the threat to the Soviet Union: discussion paper | year=1987 | journal=J R Soc Med | pages=301\u20134  | last1 = Seale | first1 = JR | last2 = Medvedev | first2 = ZA}}\n* {{cite journal | pmc = 1290815 | pmid=3612664 | volume=80 | title=Origin and transmission of AIDS. Multi-use hypodermics and the threat to the Soviet Union: discussion paper | year=1987 | journal=J R Soc Med | pages=301\u20134  | last1 = Seale | first1 = JR | last2 = Medvedev | first2 = ZA}}\n* {{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/014107688908200829 | pmid=2778789 | pmc=1292272 | volume=82 | title=Origins of the AIDS viruses: HIV-1 and HIV-2, fact or fiction? | year=1989 | journal=J R Soc Med | page=508  | last1 = Seale | first1 = J}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abel-Smith, Brian, & Kathleen Gales. (1964) ''British Doctors at Home and Abroad''. London. (LSE Occasional Papers No. 8)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seale, John}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Venereologists]]\n[[Category:Physicians of the Middlesex Hospital]]\n[[Category:Physicians of St Thomas' Hospital]]\n[[Category:AIDS origin hypotheses]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Exeter]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = John R. Seale\n| honorific_suffix = MRCP\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1927}}\n| birth_place = Exeter, England\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education =  St John's College, Cambridge\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = Theories about the origin of HIV\n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = Physician\n| field = \n| work_institutions = \n| specialism = Venereology\n| research_field = \n| notable_works = \n| prizes = \n| child = \n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''John Richard Seale''' (born 1927) is a British [[venereologist]] and advocate in the 1980s of the now-discredited theory that [[HIV]] which causes [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] might have been created in a [[bioterrorism|germ-warfare]] laboratory by [[Genetic engineering|gene-editing]]. His views and writings were subsequently used to back-up the claims of those that proposed a man-made origin for the virus, and in [[Propaganda in the Soviet Union|Soviet propaganda]] against the United States. A collection of papers relating to Seale's views on HIV are held by the [[Wellcome Collection]].\n\n==Early life and family==\nJohn Seale was born in Exeter in 1927. He received his BA from [[St John's College, Cambridge]], in 1948<ref name=coll/> and his [[MB BChir]] in 1951.<ref>''The Medical Directory 2015''. CRC Press. p. 3723. {{ISBN|978-1498705929}}</ref> He became a member of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] (MRCP) in 1953.<ref name=well/><ref name=\":Medical1986\">{{Cite book |title=The Medical Directory|last=|first= |date=1986 |publisher=Churchill Livingstone |isbn=978-0582903661 |edition=142nd |location=London |page=2670 |oclc=15467109}}</ref> Four years later he qualified with a [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]].<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\nHe married Elisabeth C. Grillet in Cambridge in 1949.<ref name=coll>\"College Notes\", ''The Eagle'', St John's College, Cambridge, 1950, p. 69.</ref><ref>\"Marriages\", ''The Times'', 7 November 1949, p. 1.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in his career, Seale took an interest in [[health economics]]. He was Goodwin Travelling Fellow for [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]] at Harvard Graduate School of Business Administration<ref name=fixed>\"Fixed Costs in the Health Service\" by J. R. Seale in ''The Lancet'', Vol. 276, No. 7152 (24 September 1960), pp. 696\u2013698.</ref> and wrote on the relative spending on medicine in different countries, publishing on the matter in ''The Lancet'' in 1960 when he was senior medical registrar at St Mary's Hospital, London, and at the West Middlesex Hospital, Isleworth.<ref name=fixed/>\n\nIn 1966, he was appointed consultant venereologist at St Thomas' Hospital in London.<ref>\"Appointments\", ''The Lancet'', 30 July 1966, p. 288.</ref> He later worked at the [[Lister Hospital, Chelsea|Lister Hospital]].<ref name=Seale1989>{{Cite journal|last=Seale|first=John|date=1 August 1989|title=Origins of the AIDS Viruses: HIV-1 and HIV-2, Fact or Fiction?|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine|language=en|volume=82|issue=8|pages=508|doi=10.1177/014107688908200829|pmid=2778789|pmc=1292272|issn=0141-0768}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]].<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\n===Anti-NHS activism===\nIn the late 1950s, Seale became a member of the [[Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine]] (FFM), a conservative organisation that resisted the state control of medicine in Britain through the [[National Health Service]] (NHS). He was elected to the Fellowship's executive in 1962.<ref name=cow/> His writings in support of the FFM's perspective included an article on \"The Supply of Doctors\" in the ''British Medical Journal'' in 1961 and another in 1964 in that journal on the rate of medical emigration from Britain and Ireland.<ref>Seale, John R. [https://www.bmj.com/content/1/5391/1173 \"Medical Emigration from Great Britain and Ireland\"],  ''British Medical Journal'', 1964, No. 1, pp. 1173\u201378.</ref> He identified migration of British doctors to countries such as Canada due to poor employment conditions in the NHS and migration to Britain of doctors from Asia whose training and English language skills he questioned, adding a racial component to the class-based and economic opposition of some British doctors to the imposition of the NHS system on them by the British government. Much of the migration from Britain was of [[general practitioner]]s in what was seen in the 1960s as a crisis in general practice. In 1962 he appeared on an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] television programme ''[[Questions in the House]]'' with fellow FFM member and member of Parliament Dr [[Donald McIntosh Johnson]] to discuss medical migration.<ref name=cow/>\n\nIn 1962 he undertook a speaking tour of the United States, funded by the [[American Medical Association]], as part of efforts to undermine the [[Kennedy administration]]'s proposed [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] bill. In a speech in New York on 21 May 1962, [[President Kennedy]] criticised Seale's arguments. After seeing this reported in London's ''Evening Standard'', Seale obtained a copy of the speech from the White House and sued the newspaper's publishers for misrepresenting the President's words.<ref name=cow/>\n\nSeale later became influential in health matters with the free-market supporting [[Institute for Economic Affairs]], contributing to their publications such as their occasional paper ''Towards a Welfare Society'' in 1967.<ref name=cow>[https://academic.oup.com/tcbh/article/26/3/424/2451908 \"Duncan Tanner Essay Prize Winner 2014: Against the 'Sacred Cow': NHS Opposition and the Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine, 1948\u201372\"] Andrew Seaton, ''[[Twentieth Century British History]]'', Vol. 26, No. 3, 1 September 2015, pp. 424\u2013449. doi:10.1093/tcbh/hwv011</ref>\n\n===Views on HIV and AIDS===\nIn the 1980s, Seale advocated the now-discredited theory that [[HIV]], which causes [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], might have been created in a germ-warfare laboratory by gene-editing and released either deliberately or by accident.<ref name=LATimes/>\n\nIn mid 1985, worried by the implications of the spread of the virus, Seale argued that it had national security implication for the west by potentially diminishing the effectiveness of NATO forces to such an extent that the Soviet Union would not need to use nuclear or chemical weapons to win a war, but he continued to believe that the virus had a natural origin in monkeys.<ref name=disin>Geissler, Erhard, and Robert Hunt Sprinkle. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/43287281 \"Disinformation Squared: Was the HIV-from-Fort-Detrick Myth a Stasi Success?\"], ''[[Politics and the Life Sciences]]'', Vol. 32, No. 2, 2013, pp. 2\u201399.</ref>\n\nLater, he began to consider the possibility that the virus was man-made after reading an article by [[Valentin Zapevalov]], \"Panic in the West: or what Hides Behind the Sensationalism of AIDS\", and an interview with professor S. Drozdov, \"AIDS: Panic Continues\", published in the non-scientific ''[[Literaturnaya Gazeta]]'' in Russia in October and December 1985  respectively. Zapevalov argued that the virus might have been produced by scientists working for the U.S. military at [[Fort Detrick]] in Maryland or at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] in Atlanta, while Drozdov said that the virus was \"apparently taken out from the deepest regions of Central Africa\" thus raising the possibility that it was deliberately collected. He also stated that the virus could have been man-made.<ref name=Seale1986/><ref name=\"Largent\">{{cite book|author=Largent, Mark A.|title=Vaccine: The Debate in Modern America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gmsPMWQgmu4C&pg=RA1-PT112|year=2012|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-1-4214-0672-5}}</ref><ref name=\"Hamb\">{{cite book|author=Hamblin, Jacob Darwin.|title=Arming Mother Nature: The Birth of Catastrophic Environmentalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNwZnNiBWUkC&pg=PA234|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-974005-5|page=234}}</ref>\n\nSeale argued that centres for biological warfare research had known about the [[Visna virus]] in sheep since 1949 which he said had a similar structure to HIV, differing by only one gene, and caused a disease with similar symptoms. He believed that HIV could have been produced by gene-editing as \"Inserting an extra gene into a virus is a routine procedure in modern genetic engineering\".<ref name=LATimes>[http://articles.latimes.com/1985-12-19/news/mn-30652_1_aids-virus AIDS Could Be Germ War Lab Product: M.D.], ''Los Angeles Times'', 19 December 1985. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref> His view that the virus could have been created in a laboratory was reported in Britain's communist ''[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]'' and on [[Radio Moscow]] who stated that it supported the possibility that the virus was made by the United States as a weapon.<ref name=disin/><ref name=med>Medvedev, Zhores A., [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1290430/ \"AIDS virus infection: A Soviet view of its origin]\". ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine''. 79 (8): 494. ISSN 0141-0768.</ref> [[Jakob Segal]], an East German biologist, later revealed to be a KGB agent, wrote to Seale in support of his views about a man-made origin for the virus.<ref name=disin/>\n\nHis views were criticised by exiled Russian dissident [[Zhores Medvedev]] in the letters page of the  ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' in August 1986 as potentially spreading Soviet disinformation.<ref name=disin/><ref name=med/> Seale's reply was printed below in which he made it clear that he did not know for sure where the virus might have been created, but maintaining the likelihood of its man-made origin. He also compared the international spread of the virus to the spread of [[myxomatosis]] in rabbits in the 1950s which had been caused by the deliberate release of two infected rabbits on an estate in France.<ref name=Seale1986>{{Cite journal|last=Seale|first=John|date=August 1986|title=Dr Seale replies|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine|volume=79|issue=8|pages=494\u2013495|issn=0141-0768|pmc=1290430}}</ref>\n\nSeale's theories were supported by his friend at St Thomas's, Henry A. Sanford, with whom he had been a medical student, and Sanford wrote in support of them in the medical and general press.<ref name=well/> Seale's views and writings, which were mostly in the form of opinion pieces, letters, and book reviews, rather than scientific papers, were used by those that advocated a man-made origin for HIV as evidence of scientific research in support of their position and may have influenced American politician [[Lyndon LaRouche]]'s views on the need to isolate those with HIV and therefore, indirectly, the proposal in California's [[1986 California Proposition 64|Proposition 64]] in 1986 to restore AIDS to the list of communicable diseases.<ref name=disin/><ref name=\"Toumey1996\">{{cite book|author=Toumey, Christopher P.|title=Conjuring Science: Scientific Symbols and Cultural Meanings in American Life|url=https://archive.org/details/conjuringscience0000toum_p4q0|url-access=registration|year=1996|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick|isbn=978-0-8135-2285-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/conjuringscience0000toum_p4q0/page/88 88]}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1987, Seale argued in a paper given before the [[Bristol Medico Chirurgical Society]], and later printed in their journal, that the threat from AIDS was so serious that only compulsory government testing and methods to prevent homosexual men infecting each other and non-homosexuals could halt it with an inevitable and justified curtailment of civil rights as occurs when a country faces war. He further argued that the use of condoms would have no effect on the spread of the disease as, in his view, dirty needles, blood, and serum were the most effective methods of transmission. He also blamed homosexuals among AIDS scientists and campaigners for perpetuating, in his view, incorrect ideas about the spread of the disease.<ref>Seale, John R. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5113556/ \"The AIDS Epidemic and Its Control\"], ''Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal'', Vol. 102, No. 3 (August 1987), pp. 66\u201368.</ref> In May 1987, Seale and [[Zhores A. Medvedev]] argued in an article in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'' that HIV in Russia was spread primarily through the re-use of poorly sterilised hypodermic needles rather than through sexual activity.<ref name=\"russ\">{{cite book|author=Mark G. Field & Judyth L. Twigg (Eds.)|title=Russia's Torn Safety Nets: Health and Social Welfare During the Transition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VsoYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA149|year=2000|publisher=St Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-349-62712-7|page=149}}</ref><ref>\"Origin and transmission of AIDS. Multi-use hypodermics and the threat to the Soviet Union: discussion paper\", John R. Seale & Zhores A. Medvedev, ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'', Vol. 80 (May 1987), pp. 201\u2013204.</ref>\n\nRecords relating to Seale's theories and his supporter Henry A. Sanford are held in the [[Wellcome Collection]] which received them from Sanford in 2013.<ref name=\"well\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.wellcomelibrary.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=(AltRefNo=%27MS.8877%27)|title=Henry Sanford: papers relating to John Seale and controversies over AIDS|last=|first=|date=|website=Wellcome Library|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===1960s===\n* \"[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140673660917670 Fixed Costs in the Health Service]\", ''The Lancet'', Vol. 276, No. 7152 (24 September 1960), pp.&nbsp;696\u2013698. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(60)91767-0\n* \"The Supply of Doctors\", ''British Medical Journal'', 2, 9 December 1961, 2, pp.&nbsp;1554\u201355.\n* ''The Supply of Doctors and the Future of the British Medical Profession''. Fellowship for Freedom in Medicine, London, 1962.\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/1/5391/1173 \"Medical Emigration from Great Britain and Ireland\"],  ''British Medical Journal'', 1964, No. 1, pp.&nbsp;1173\u201378.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1047771/pdf/brjvendis00103-0034.pdf \"Sexually Transmitted Diseases and Marriage\"], ''[[British Journal of Venereal Diseases]]'', Vol. 42 (1966), No. 31, pp.&nbsp;31\u201336. {{PMID|5952270}}\n\n===1970s===\n*\"Vaginal discharge\" in [[Geoffrey Chamberlain]] (Ed.) (1977) ''Contemporary Obstetrics and Gynaecology''. London: Northwood.<ref name=\":Medical1986\"/>\n\n===1980s===\n* [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/014107688507800801 \"AIDS Virus Infection: Prognosis and Transmission\"], ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'', Vol. 78, No. 8 (1 August 1985), pp.&nbsp;613\u2013615.\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5113556/ \"The AIDS Epidemic and Its Control\"], ''[[Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal]]'', Vol. 102, No. 3 (August 1987), pp.&nbsp;66\u201368.\n* \"Kuru, AIDS and Aberrant Social Behaviour\", ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'', Vol. 80, No. 4 (1 April 1987), pp.&nbsp;200\u2013202. https://doi.org/10.1177/014107688708000402\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1290815/ \"Origin and transmission of AIDS. Multi-use hypodermics and the threat to the Soviet Union: discussion paper\"], John R. Seale & Zhores A. Medvedev, ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine'', Vol. 80 (May 1987), pp.&nbsp;201\u2013204.\n* [https://europepmc.org/backend/ptpmcrender.fcgi?accid=PMC1290815&blobtype=pdf \"Origins of the AIDS Viruses: HIV-1 and HIV-2, Fact or Fiction?\", ''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine''], Vol. 82, No. 8 (1 August 1989), p.&nbsp;508. https://doi.org/10.1177/014107688908200829\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abel-Smith, Brian, & Kathleen Gales. (1964) ''British Doctors at Home and Abroad''. London. (LSE Occasional Papers No. 8)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seale, John}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Venereologists]]\n[[Category:Physicians of the Middlesex Hospital]]\n[[Category:Physicians of St Thomas' Hospital]]\n[[Category:AIDS origin hypotheses]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Exeter]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_R._Seale"}
